06170nam a22007695i 9780773588745DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2016364925  a97807735887457 a10.1515/97807735887452doi  a(DE-B1597)654577  a(OCoLC)829421931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aBL625.9.I55bG76 2013 4aBL2530.C2 ǂb G76 2013eb 7aSOC0260102bisacsh04a200.81 aBeyer, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGrowing Up Canadian :bMuslims, Hindus, Buddhists /cPeter Beyer, Rubina Ramji. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b17 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Ethnic History ;v23200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables And Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tGrowing Up Canadian: Systemic and Lived Religion -- tData and Methods: University Settings in Toronto, Ottawa, and Montreal -- tYoung Adults and Religion in Canada: A Statistical Overview -- tIslam, Hinduism, and Buddhism: Differential Reconstruction of Religions -- tFrom Atheism to Open Religiosity: Muslim Men -- tA Variable but Convergent Islam: Muslim Women -- tPerpetuating Religion and Culture: Hindu Women -- tA Dominance of Marginal Relations: Hindu Men -- tMaybe, in the Future: Buddhist Men -- tFluid Boundaries of a Tolerant Religion: Buddhist Women -- tThe Difference that Gender Makes -- tGrowing Up in Toronto: Muslims, Hindus, Buddhists -- tGrowing Up in Canada, the United States, and Western Europe -- tReligion among Immigrant Youth in Canada -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA significant number of Canadian-raised children from post-1970s immigrant families have reached adulthood over the past decade. As a result, the demographics of religious affiliation are changing across Canada. Growing Up Canadian is the first comparative study of religion among young adults of Muslim, Hindu, and Buddhist immigrant families. Contributors consider how relating to religion varies significantly depending on which faith is in question, how men and women have different views on the role of religion in their lives, and how the possibilities of being religiously different are greater in larger urban centres than in surrounding rural communities. Interviews with over two hundred individuals, aged 18 to 26, reveal that few are drawn to militant, politicized religious extremes, how almost all second generation young adults take personal responsibility for their religion, and want to understand the reasons for their beliefs and practices. The first major study of religion among this generation in Canada, Growing Up Canadian is an important contribution to understanding religious diversity and multiculturalism in the twenty-first century. Contributors include Peter Beyer, Kathryn Carrière, Wendy Martin, and Lori Beaman (University of Ottawa), Rubina Ramji (Cape Breton University), Nancy Nason-Clark and Cathy Holtmann (University of New Brunswick), Shandip Saha (Athabasca University), John H. Simpson (University of Toronto), and Marie-Paule Martel-Reny (Concordia University)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBuddhist youthxReligious lifexCanada. 0aBuddhist youthxReligious lifezCanada. 0aChildren of immigrantsxReligious lifexCanada. 0aChildren of immigrantsxReligious lifezCanada. 0aHindu youthxReligious lifexCanada. 0aHindu youthxReligious lifezCanada. 0aMuslim youthxReligious lifexCanada. 0aMuslim youthxReligious lifezCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aBeaman, Lori, econtrib